{{Infobox language |name=Judeo-Yemeni Arabic |states=[[Israel]], [[Yemen]] |ethnicity=[[Yemenite Jews]] |speakers=50,000 |date=1995 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Semitic languages|Semitic]] |fam3=[[Central Semitic languages|Central Semitic]] |fam4=[[Arabic languages]] |fam5=[[Peninsular Arabic|Peninsular]] |script=[[Hebrew alphabet]] |iso3=jye |glotto=jude1267 |glottorefname=Judeo-Yemeni Arabic }}
'''Judeo-Yemeni Arabic''' (also known as Judeo-Yemeni and Yemenite Judeo-Arabic) is a [[varieties of Arabic|variety of Arabic]] spoken by Jews living or formerly living in Yemen. The language is quite different from mainstream [[Yemeni Arabic]], and is written in the [[Hebrew alphabet]]. The cities of [[Sana'a]], [[Aden]], [[Al Bayda, Yemen|al-Bayda]], and [[Habban District]] and the villages in their districts each have (or had) their own dialect.<ref name="e18"/>
The vast majority of [[Yemenite Jews]] have [[Yemenite Jews in Israel|relocated to Israel]] and have [[language shift|shifted]] to [[Modern Hebrew]] as their [[first language]]. In 1995, Israel was home to 50,000 speakers of Judeo-Yemeni in 1995, while 1,000 remained in Yemen.<ref name=e18/> According to Yemeni rabbi al-Marhabi, most of these have since left for the United States. {{as of|2010}}, fewer than 300 Jews were believed to remain in Yemen.<ref>{{cite news|last=Berer|first=Josh|date=2010-01-06||title=Caught in Strife, Yemen’s Jews Cling Fiercely to Their Ancient Heritage|url=http://forward.com/news/122780/caught-in-strife-yemen-s-jews-cling-fiercely-to/|newspaper=Forward|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref>
